<h1>Military Innovations</h1>
<p>One of Napoleon’s greatest innovations was his skilful use of artillery. Cannon had existed for several centuries, but Napoleon turned them from merely a useful addition to an army into a lethal weapon that could win battles almost single-handedly. He referred to them as his “beautiful daughters”, and was fond of praising their importance in warfare. At Waterloo, Napoleon delayed the start of the battle solely so that his artillery could be used to maximum effect, without being clogged by the mud. At Wagram, 112 French cannon tore an advancing Austrian army to pieces, inflicting a crushing defeat. At Friedland, too, the artillery wreaked havoc in the ranks of the retreating Russian army.  </p>
<p>Like many other successful generals, he also mastered the art of rapid movement, and deceiving his opponents through careful manoeuvring. On multiple occasions, he vanquished numerically superior foes by ambushing and destroying one army before wheeling around and crushing the other, denying them the chance to unite and use their superior numbers to defeat him. Even in 1814, when coalition armies were sweeping into France from all sides, Napoleon inflicted four defeats on his enemies in less than a week, though this ultimately proved insufficient for him to avoid overall defeat.</p>
