<h1>Military Record</h1>
<p>Napoleon’s military record is formidable. He fought a total of 60 battles, and lost only 7 of them. Austria and Prussia in particular faced countless defeats at his hands, and some of his victories – Austerlitz, Jena, Marengo, to name but a few, are still regarded as some of the greatest feats of military strategy ever achieved. Napoleon almost always faced a severe numerical disadvantage, and was usually going up against enemies that were significantly better funded (thanks to British subsidies) and often had naval dominance (especially after Trafalgar, British naval dominance was unquestioned). He took control of a nation that was still recovering from the aftermath of a vicious revolution. France had made itself into an enemy of all of Europe due to its anti-monarchism, and had had to fight multiple desperate wars of survival to even stay intact. Yet in just fifteen years under Napoleon, France defeated its enemies time and time again, establishing the closest thing to a European empire the world had ever seen. Napoleon won a truly remarkable series of victories – in the end, it took not one but seven coalitions of European nations to finally bring him down. Much of the time, a single defeat at the hands of Napoleon could bring a nation to its knees, and force them out of a coalition war. Few leaders have ever come close to such a record. </p>
</section>
